# Grounded Extraction Protocol

This rule tells the orchestrating agent how to read a corpus into the
zettelkasten **against a goal** using the grounded-extraction pipeline. It fires
when the user wants to pull a set of sources (papers, repos, a PM's letters,
product pages) into the knowledge graph against a rubric -- e.g. "how was this
system built and what decisions were made," "this PM's transferable decision
behavior," "a lit-review matrix," "every statistic + its grounding quote."

This bundle is only available when the zettelkasten capability is enabled for
the project (the coordinator's `agents(action="list")` shows `extractor` / `scribe` /
`auditor`, and `create_extraction_graph` exists). If they are absent, the project
was set up without `--with-zettelkasten`; tell the user.

## The pipeline

A grounded-extraction run is one fixed pipeline applied to N sources, all
parameterized by a single **schema** (the rubric):

```
per source:  [prep: ingest + seed hub note]  ->  extractor (planner, parallel)
                                              ->  scribe   (implementer, serialized)
                                              ->  auditor  (checker)
then once:    linker (cross-source links)     ->  synthesizer (author spine prose)
                                              ->  memory (record)
```

- **extractor** (read-only planner): reads the ingested source against the
  SCHEMA and emits grounded claim+quote candidates mapped to the schema's
  dimensions. Extractors run **in parallel** across sources.
- **scribe** (implementer): commits candidates as `claim` + `quote` note pairs in
  the source's graph, tagged with the schema dimension tags and linked to the
  per-source **hub** note. Scribes are **serialized** -- the coordinator's
  write-lease already enforces one writer at a time, so never run two in a wave.
- **auditor** (checker, different model family): verifies grounding integrity
  (every claim has a verbatim supporting quote) and **schema-dimension coverage**.

## How a schema is selected and injected

A schema is to an extraction task what `model` already is to every task: a named
attribute the coordinator resolves and flows into task context.

1. **Pick or author a schema.**
   - Reuse a registry schema by name (see `extraction-schemas.yaml` shipped with
     the bundle: `architecture-extraction`, `lit-review-matrix`,
     `statistic-extraction`).
   - Or author a new one (see the authoring guide below) in the project's
     `extraction-schemas.yaml` (next to `agents.yaml`, in `.cursor/` or
     `.claude/`). Restart the coordinator MCP server after editing it.
2. **The coordinator flows it for you.** When a task carries `schema: <name>`,
   the coordinator expands the rubric and puts the full schema object in that
   task's context (`get_task_context` -> `task.schema`). You do NOT re-read the
   registry.
3. **Paste the same dimension block into all three roles' prompts.** When you
   assemble the extractor / scribe / auditor prompts, include the schema's
   `dimensions` (tag + desc + any `claim_framing`) verbatim so all three share
   one rubric. `create_extraction_graph` already stamps `schema` on every task,
   so the object is present in context; surface it in the prompt text too.

### Prompt Assembly for the trio

For each trio task, build the prompt as:

```
<persona from agents(action="get", agent=<extractor|scribe|auditor>)>

TASK: <description from get_task_context>
PROJECT: <project>
SOURCE: <source graph name with ingested fulltext>
HUB: <hub note id> (graph: <source>)
SLICE: <"full", or the assigned window for a sliced book>
SLICE_READ: <for a sliced source only: the exact source(action="fulltext", ...)
        windowed call the extractor/scribe must use to read this slice>
SCHEMA: <paste the WHOLE schema: dimensions (each {tag, desc, claim_framing?,
        note_type?, connect_to?}) AND the relations backbone (`relations` +
        any per-dimension `connect_to`/`relation`) if the schema declares one>
SPINE: <when the schema has a `synthesis` block: the materialized spine prep
        pre-created -- the synthesis graph name, apex id, attach_relation, and the
        dimension tag->node-id map. `create_extraction_graph` stamps this into each
        task's context automatically; paste it for the scribe + auditor>
LINK_RELATION: <schema.link_relation>   # scribe + auditor
```

The scribe also receives the extractor's CANDIDATES (from the predecessor task
output). Keep the SCHEMA block identical across all three roles -- and include the
backbone: it is the relations template the scribe instantiates and the auditor
checks, so dropping it collapses the graph back into a hub-and-spokes dandelion.

## Prep / ingest mechanics (and why prep is not a graph task)

A planner (extractor) **cannot depend on an implementer** (graph validation
enforces this), so the ingest + hub-seeding cannot be a graph task -- it must
happen before the extractor runs. `create_extraction_graph` does this for you,
synchronously, tool-side: for each source it runs `source(action="ingest", path=...)`
-> `source(action="create", content_hash=..., source_path=..., <metadata>)`, then
seeds the per-source hub note per the schema's `hub` block and captures its id.
If you build the graph by hand instead, do this prep yourself first.

## Driving a run

1. Call `create_extraction_graph(sources, schema, project, target_entry_id?,
   synthesis_label?)`. It ingests, seeds hubs, and -- when the schema declares a
   `synthesis` block -- pre-creates the materialized spine (synthesis graph + apex
   + dimension nodes, registered as a project source) under `synthesis_label`
   (defaults to the project name). It builds the `extractor -> scribe -> auditor`
   DAG (+ a trailing `memory` task) and returns `{run_id, task_ids, graph, sources,
   structure?, graph_summary}` -- `structure` (the synthesis graph + apex/spec ids
   + dimension tag->node map) is present iff the schema materialized a spine.
2. Drive the normal wave loop: `get_ready_tasks` -> `claim_task` -> spawn the
   subagent (Prompt Assembly above) -> `submit_result`. Remember scribes are
   serialized (a second `claim_task` on an implementer returns `blocked`).
3. **Batch:** run a pilot batch (`batch_size=N`, e.g. 2-3 sources), verify the
   scribe's tags and the auditor's coverage matrix look right, then fan out the
   rest.

## Book-scale sources (automatic slicing)

A paper is one trio; a 500-666pg book is not. `create_extraction_graph` slices a
large source natively -- you do NOT hand-build per-chapter DAGs or force-refresh
caches:

- **Whole-document cache.** Prep ingests a run's sources with the full document
  cached (plus a page/outline sidecar), so a later chapter is physically present.
  The 200k cap now bounds only what a single `source(action="fulltext")` READ
  returns, not what is stored.
- **Per-slice fan-out.** A source above ~200k chars / ~60 pages is split into
  windows -- snapped to the PDF's chapter bookmarks when present, else fixed char
  windows with a small overlap. Each slice gets its own `extractor -> scribe`
  pair sharing the one per-source hub, and a SINGLE `auditor` per source runs
  after all its scribes (so coverage stays whole-source). A source at/below the
  threshold keeps the exact single-trio shape.
- **The returned graph names the fan-out.** `graph_summary.extractor_slices` and
  `sliced_sources` (`[{name, slices}]`) report which sources fanned out. Slice
  extractor aliases are `ext_{i}_{k}` (vs `ext_{i}` for a single-trio source).
- **The extractor reads its window.** Each sliced task carries a `SLICE_READ`
  line -- the exact `source(action="fulltext", offset=.../page_start=...)` call
  that returns that slice. Paste it into the extractor/scribe prompt; quotes must
  be verbatim substrings of the returned window.
- **Overrides.** Pass an explicit `slices` list on a source (page ranges
  `{page_start, page_end}`, char ranges `{char_start, char_end}`, or chapter
  titles `{chapter: "<bookmark title>"}`), or tune `slice_window` /
  `slice_overlap` / `slice_threshold` on the call.

## The cross-source linker pass (after scribes)

After the per-source scribes have run, do a cross-source linker pass: it needs
the global view of sibling note ids, so it is an orchestrator/human step, not a
per-source graph task. Use `note(action="search")` / `suggest` to find notes
that share a dimension tag across sources and link related claims (e.g. one
system's `topology` answer to another's). This is where the schema pays off as an
index (next section). Then let the `memory` task record the run.

## The synthesis stage (authoring the spine prose)

When the schema declares a `synthesis` policy, prep pre-creates the spine nodes
EMPTY: each apex/dimension node carries `synthesis_status: scaffold` and a
placeholder "claims attach here" body. The scribes attach every source's claims
to those nodes, but the nodes' own PROSE is authored by no shipped agent. So
after the auditors (and the linker pass) there is one more orchestrator/human
step -- the **synthesizer** -- which reads each dimension's grounding, writes the
node body, and flips `synthesis_status` to `materialized`.

Per dimension node (then the apex last):

1. **Roll up the grounding in one call.** A dimension's claims live in the
   per-source graphs (attached cross-graph), so use the project-scoped incoming
   follow -- no custom script needed:

```
note(action="follow", graph=<synthesis-graph>, note_id=<dimension-node>,
     relation="input-to", direction="incoming", project=<project>)
```

   Its `cross_graph_backlinks` are every source's claims for that dimension --
   the evidence to synthesize from.

2. **Write the body in the house format**, grounded ONLY in those claims:
   - a **bold one-line headline** -- the dimension's through-line across sources;
   - a **grounded paragraph** -- the synthesis, every assertion traceable to a
     rolled-up claim (introduce no ungrounded judgments);
   - a closing footer: *"Grounded in N claims across M sources feed this node."*

   REPLACE the skeleton's placeholder sentence rather than appending above it:

```
note(action="update", graph=<synthesis-graph>, note_id=<dimension-node>,
     replace_body=<authored body>, synthesis_status="materialized")
```

3. **The apex last.** Once every dimension is materialized, synthesize the apex
   portrait the same way (its grounding is the dimension nodes rolling up into
   it) and flip its `synthesis_status` too.

Track what is left with `schema(action="spines")`: each spine reports an
`incomplete` list (apex/dimensions still `scaffold`) and a `materialized` flag,
so "which personas are unfinished?" is one query -- not body-char-count forensics.

## The payoff: tag -> note-tag -> queryable comparison

Each schema dimension's `tag` becomes the **note tag** the scribe writes. After a
run, notes tagged `decision-sizing` / `topology` / `autonomy-placement` exist
across every source. So the schema is simultaneously the **extraction rubric and
the cross-source comparison index**: query one tag and line up every system's
answer. Treat the schema as the index -- author tags you will want to compare on.

## The data-grounding half: grounding a claim by re-computation

Everything above grounds a claim in a **verbatim quote** (the prose trio
`extractor -> scribe -> auditor`). A claim can instead be grounded in a
**re-computable statistic over a stored dataset** -- `grounding.method='data'`,
verified by the auditor RE-RUNNING the computation rather than string-matching.
This is the THIRD grounding modality alongside `quote` and `equation`. angelo
VERIFIES and STORES this evidence; it NEVER composes beliefs from it -- a
derivation is an opaque, deterministic function angelo can only invoke and
compare. The application that consumes these verified cells (e.g. a genome
estimator) is what composes them; the generalist store does not.

### When the data trio runs

A source declared `kind: data` in `create_extraction_graph` references an
EXISTING zettelkasten dataset box (its `graph`) plus a list of `derivations`,
SKIPS document ingest, and builds a `data-extractor -> data-scribe -> auditor`
trio instead of the prose trio. Under the same `synthesis_label`, a data trio
and a prose trio attach to ONE shared spine -- a data claim threads the same
dimension nodes as a prose claim, so the synthesizer/matrix treat them alike. A
source with no `kind` is a prose source and is unaffected (byte-identical path).

### The `evidence: data` dimension + its derivation

A schema dimension declares which grounding channel it expects:

```yaml
dimensions:
  - {tag: sizing, desc: "position concentration", evidence: data,
     derivation: freischutz.concentration.mean_top5}
```

`evidence` is `text` (default -- the verbatim-quote channel) or `data` (a
dimension a registered derivation can ground). `evidence: data` is GENERIC: it
says the dimension CAN be data-grounded, nothing about what the derivation
means. The `derivation` id is either an `expr` (a whitelisted expression --
`mean:col` / `quantile:col:0.9` / `sum:col`) that re-verifies anywhere with no
host registration, or a REGISTERED id (`freischutz.concentration.mean_top5`)
contributed by host code (same trust boundary as `agents.yaml`). Prose and data
dimensions coexist in one schema; only `evidence: data` dimensions are the data
trio's job.

### Prompt assembly for the data trio

The data trio reuses the prose Prompt Assembly with a data-source header:

```
<persona from agents(action="get", agent=<data-extractor|data-scribe|auditor>)>

TASK: <description from get_task_context>
PROJECT: <project>
SOURCE: <dataset box name -- read its type=dataset notes via dataset(action="values")>
HUB: <hub note id> (graph: <source>)
DERIVATIONS: <the source's declared derivation ids>
SCHEMA: <the whole schema; attend to the evidence:data dimensions + their derivation>
STRUCTURE: <as for the prose trio, when the schema materializes a spine>
```

- **data-extractor** (planner, read-only): reads the dataset box's `type=dataset`
  notes (`dataset(action="values"|"get")`) and, for each `evidence: data`
  dimension, emits a DATA_CANDIDATE -- a proposed data-citation (`dataset_note`,
  `derivation_id`, `selection`, expected `value`, `epistemic_status`,
  `confidence`). It does not write; it emits a `question` candidate for a
  dimension whose data is missing rather than inventing a value.
- **data-scribe** (implementer): commits each candidate as a `claim`/`finding`
  note with a `method: data` grounding, sets `epistemic_status`, and attaches it
  to the schema's dimension node via the SAME `note(action="attach")` seam the
  prose scribe uses (the server resolves the node, relation, and edge direction).
  A data claim needs NO supporting quote note -- its evidence is the citation.

### The `method: data` citation shape

The data-scribe writes it via `note(action="add", ..., grounding=…,
epistemic_status=…)`:

```yaml
grounding:
  method: data
  dataset_note: <a type=dataset note id (+ its graph)>
  dataset_hash: <the dataset's pinned content_hash>   # from dataset(action="snapshot")
  selection: {where: "quarter >= 2005-01-01"}          # deterministic row/col filter
  derivation_id: mean:top5_concentration               # an expr OR a registered id
  derivation_version: 3                                 # omit for an expr
  params: {seed: 7}                                     # e.g. an RNG seed for a fit; omit if none
  value: 0.68                                           # the asserted result
  tolerance: 1.0e-6                                     # abs (rel_tolerance also accepted)
  confidence: 0.9                                       # opaque: stored/displayed, never computed with
epistemic_status: measured
```

- `dataset_hash` + `derivation_id` + `derivation_version` + `selection` +
  `params` are the reproducibility pin. Pin the dataset FIRST with
  `dataset(action="snapshot")` so the citation grounds on a frozen frame.
- `epistemic_status` is `grounded` (a verified quote/equation), `measured` (a
  directly-observed statistic -- mean/quantile/…), or `inferred` (a fitted
  quantity -- an inverse-optimization / model fit). Descriptive `expr`
  derivations are `measured`; a derivation declared `fit: true` is `inferred`.
- The scribe does NOT stamp `verified`/`verified_at`/`verified_in` -- those are
  the auditor's on a clean re-run. `confidence`/`validation`/`method_meta` are
  OPAQUE: angelo stores and surfaces them but never computes with them (it only
  shape-checks that a present `validation` is a `{kind, ...}` dict).

### The auditor: recompute + epistemic-status reporting

The auditor gains a recompute check alongside the quote check. For each
`method: data` claim it calls
`note(action="verify_grounding", note_id=<claim id>, graph=<SOURCE>)`, which
re-resolves the pinned dataset, re-runs the `derivation_id`, and compares the
result to the asserted `value` within `tolerance`. It does NOT trust the stored
`verified` stamp. Outcomes split two tiers:

- **HARD violation** (blocks coverage, like an unverified quote -- angelo COULD
  re-run and it disagreed): `dataset_hash_mismatch` (the pinned data changed),
  `value_not_reproduced` (re-run disagrees beyond `tolerance`),
  `nondeterministic_unpinned` (a `deterministic=False` derivation with no pinned
  `seed`), `validation_malformed` (`validation` present but not a `{kind, ...}`
  dict). These surface as `unreproduced_data_claims` in the coverage audit.
- **SOFT unavailable** (informational, NOT a defect -- the claim RETAINS its
  prior `verified`/`verified_in` stamp): `derivation_unavailable` (the id is not
  registered here -- expected for a fitted claim off-site) and
  `dataset_unavailable` (the dataset note isn't resolvable here). A descriptive
  `expr` claim re-verifies anywhere, so a soft outcome on one means a genuinely
  missing dataset.

A clean reproduce flips `grounding.verified` to true and stamps `verified_at` +
`verified_in`; a verified data claim counts as covered exactly like a
quote-backed claim. The auditor also reports, per dimension, the
EPISTEMIC-STATUS MIX -- `{grounded, measured, inferred}` -- so "is this dimension
verbatim, measured, or fitted?" is answerable from the ledger, not char-count
forensics.

## A schema is two policies: an extraction policy AND a synthesis policy

Authoring a schema means deciding BOTH halves, not just the first. Leaving the
second implicit is what strands a run half-done with no way to tell (see the
cautionary example below).

- **Extraction policy** -- how claims come OUT of each source: the `dimensions`
  (the tags to pull + their `desc`/`claim_framing`), `grounded`/`strict`, and the
  per-source `hub`. This half decides what the extractor looks for and what the
  scribe commits per source. It has a built-in finish line: the auditor's
  grounding + coverage check.
- **Synthesis policy** -- how those per-source claims ROLL UP into a shared
  spine. Choose one **on purpose**:
  - a `synthesis` block (the materialized spine -- an apex node + one node per
    dimension that every source's claims attach to), OR
  - a deliberate flat checklist (no `synthesis` block -- every claim links to its
    source hub; right for goals like `statistic-extraction` where there is
    nothing to roll up).
  Do not let this default by omission -- "no synthesis block" must be a decision,
  not an oversight.

The synthesis half does NOT yet auto-complete: prep pre-creates the spine nodes,
but the apex/dimension-node *prose* is authored by hand after the scribes run. So
a schema that declares a synthesis policy is only DONE once that prose is written
-- until then the spine is a skeleton, not a portrait.

> **Cautionary example -- pm-personas.** The persona schemas were authored with a
> clear extraction policy, but the synthesis policy was treated as tribal
> knowledge. Several personas (Lynch, Livermore) were left as empty spine
> skeletons -- the dimension/apex nodes existed, but their portrait prose was
> never written, and nothing flagged them as unfinished. The only way to tell a
> half-done persona from a finished one was to measure body char-counts. Author
> the synthesis policy explicitly so "is this persona finished?" is answerable
> from the schema, not from forensics.

## One spine per instance vs one pooled spine (the comparison-matrix decision)

Before driving a run whose schema declares a `synthesis` block, decide the spine
GRANULARITY -- it is as load-bearing as the schema choice and it is easy to get
wrong by omission. The lever is `synthesis_label`: **each distinct label mints its
own `{label}` synthesis graph (one spine); all sources run under the same label
roll their claims up into ONE pooled spine.** `synthesis_label` defaults to the
project name, so a naive single run pools the WHOLE corpus into one spine.

Choose by the goal:

- **Comparison corpus (N comparable instances of the same kind).** When the
  sources describe DISTINCT instances you want to line up side by side -- multiple
  PMs, multiple hedge-fund architectures, competing products, different models --
  you want **one spine per instance**, not one pool. Every instance's spine shares
  the schema's dimension column-keys -- that shared column-key set is the
  **spine-schema** (the grouping rubric, distinct from this extraction `schema`) --
  so they **auto-unite into a spine-group matrix** (each instance = one row, each
  dimension = one column) -- the comparison surface the schema's tags were chosen
  for. Drive it by giving each instance its own
  `synthesis_label` (run the pipeline once per instance), and group multiple
  sources that describe the SAME instance under ONE label (e.g. two papers on the
  same system -> one spine). This is exactly the shape `pm-personas` uses: one
  spine per investor, united into a "Decision Profile" matrix.
- **Single-subject corpus (one thing, many sources).** When the sources are many
  views of ONE subject (one system's docs, one company's filings), a single pooled
  spine under one label is correct -- there is one thing to synthesize.

The ONLY non-mechanical step is deciding which sources are the same instance (a
model/human judgment over the corpus); once labels are assigned the attach is
deterministic. If a corpus was already extracted as one POOLED spine and you later
want the per-instance comparison, re-partition it: split the pool into one
per-instance spine (sharing the same dimension column-keys so they join the
matrix) and retire the pool -- do NOT leave both, or the pool shows up as a stray
matrix row. Filling several EXISTING spines from one run is the `spines=[...]` +
`multi_spine=True` path; minting fresh per-instance spines is the per-label path
above.

Pick this on purpose. Defaulting to the project-name label silently pools a
comparison corpus into a single spine -- the same "decide the synthesis policy
explicitly" failure as leaving a spine's prose unwritten.

## Generating a schema (the extraction helper)

A schema is the FOCUS RUBRIC a run reads documents through, so authoring one is the
first step when a user wants to look at a corpus "with a certain focus." You can
hand-write the YAML (below), or generate it with the zettelkasten `schema` tool --
you supply the judgment, the tool guarantees a valid block:

1. Check what's already there: `schema(action="spines")` lists the materialized
   spines this project has built (apex type + dimension tags). When extending an
   existing spine, mirror its shape rather than starting cold. Then, from the
   user's focus goal, draft a `spec` dict: `dimensions` (the tags you'll want to
   compare on), an optional `relations` backbone, and -- for a real spine -- a
   `synthesis` block. Ground the dimensions in the corpus when sources exist by
   reading a sample with `source(action="fulltext")`; the goal alone is enough when
   there are no documents yet.
2. `schema(action="validate", name=..., spec=...)` -- expands the draft WITHOUT
   writing; fix any reported error (dangling tag ref, invalid relation/type).
3. `schema(action="save", name=..., spec=...)` -- writes the validated block into
   the project's `extraction-schemas.yaml`. Then RESTART the coordinator +
   zettelkasten MCP servers (the registry is cached at load) before the new schema
   is usable in `create_extraction_graph`.

`schema(action="list")` / `schema(action="get", name=...)` inspect the registry;
`schema(action="spines")` discovers the live materialized spines in the current
project (model or extend them instead of a shipped example).

## Authoring a new schema

Add a block to the project's `extraction-schemas.yaml`:

```yaml
my-rubric:
  description: "One line: what this rubric extracts."
  grounded: true          # require a verbatim contiguous quote per claim (default true)
  strict: true            # reject a written note lacking a valid schema tag (default true)
  link_relation: component-of   # relation from each claim note -> the source's hub
  hub:                    # how to seed the per-source hub note
    type: model           # a zettelkasten note type (model, concept, ...)
    title_template: "{source_title}: Overview"   # {source_title}/{persona}/{source}/{year}
  dimensions:
    - {tag: my-dimension, desc: "what to look for", claim_framing: "optional framing hint"}
    - {tag: another,      desc: "...", note_type: finding}
  relations:              # OPTIONAL relations backbone (the intended spine)
    - {from: another, to: my-dimension, relation: depends-on}
```

Field contract:
- `tag` IS the contract -- it becomes the note tag (the comparison index) and the
  auditor's coverage-matrix row. **Tags must be unique within a schema.** Choose
  tags you will want to query and compare across sources.
- `grounded: false` is for goals with no quotable source (e.g. synthesizing
  across many inputs); the scribe then skips the quote-note + grounding step.
- `strict: false` relaxes the tag-required check (use sparingly -- it weakens the
  index).
- `claim_framing` / `note_type` are optional per-dimension hints passed to the
  extractor (and they steer the scribe's note type).
- `evidence` (`text` default | `data`) picks the dimension's grounding channel: a
  `data` dimension is grounded by a re-computable statistic instead of a quote,
  and names its `derivation` (an `expr` like `mean:col`, or a registered id). See
  "The data-grounding half" above.

### Shape: make the schema a template, not just a checklist

Plain dimensions produce a *checklist* -- the scribe can only safely attach every
claim to the hub, yielding a flat dandelion. Declare the intended **shape** so the
scribe builds a real spine. Two complementary mechanisms (use either or both):

- **`relations`** (top-level): the backbone edges *between dimensions*, each
  `{from, to, relation}` where `from`/`to` are dimension tags and `relation` is a
  valid zettelkasten relation. The scribe wires these between each dimension's
  representative claims -- but only where the source actually supports the edge
  (the extractor confirms each; unsupported ones are skipped, not fabricated).
- **per-dimension `connect_to` + `relation`**: a dimension's claims attach to
  *another dimension's node* (a parent) instead of the hub. This is how you build
  hierarchy -- the parent carries the path to the hub, so a `connect_to` dimension
  is one level deeper rather than another spoke.

```yaml
  dimensions:
    - {tag: topology,      desc: "the backbone shape"}              # the spine root
    - {tag: orchestration, desc: "...", connect_to: topology, relation: depends-on}
    - {tag: evaluation,    desc: "..."}
  relations:
    - {from: evaluation, to: topology, relation: motivated-by}
```

#### The strongest form: a `synthesis` block (materialized spine)

`relations`/`connect_to` alone still wire edges between per-source *representative
claims* -- there is no durable node to hold synthesis, so at N sources x ~60
claims the graph fans into a dandelion. A **`synthesis` block** fixes this: prep
PRE-CREATES a persistent spine -- an apex synthesis node + one node per dimension,
in a DEDICATED synthesis graph (added as a normal project source) -- and the
scribe ATTACHES each source's claims to the matching dimension node instead of the
hub. The spine is then `claim -> dimension node -> synthesis (apex) -> hub`:
O(dimensions) per run, with the dimension/apex nodes as a real synthesis surface.

```yaml
my-rubric:
  link_relation: input-to
  synthesis:
    graph: "{label}-profile"               # dedicated graph; {label}/{persona}/{project}/{schema}
    node: {type: synthesis, title_template: "{label}: Profile", link_relation: related}
    dimension_node:
      type: concept
      title_template: "{label} - {dimension}"
      attach_relation: input-to            # claim --input-to--> its dimension node
      relation: component-of               # dimension node --component-of--> apex
    spec: {type: model, title_template: "{label}: Spec", relation: derives-from}  # optional
  dimensions:
    - {tag: attends-to, desc: "..."}       # materialize: false opts a dimension out
  relations:
    - {from: ranking-rule, to: attends-to, relation: depends-on}  # wired between dimension NODES
```

With a `synthesis` block: every field defaults (a minimal `synthesis: {graph: "..."}`
works); each dimension materializes a node unless it sets `materialize: false`;
top-level `relations` are wired between the materialized dimension nodes (stable
across sources), not representative claims. `{label}` comes from
`create_extraction_graph`'s `synthesis_label` (defaults to the project name).
The YAML above is a complete worked example.

Validation is strict and happens at expand time: every `from`/`to`/`connect_to`
must reference a real dimension tag, a dimension cannot `connect_to` itself, and
every relation (including `link_relation`) must be in the zettelkasten relation
vocabulary -- a malformed backbone surfaces as a schema error, not a silent
flatten. Schemas with no backbone keep behaving as a flat checklist (the claim ->
hub `link_relation` for every dimension), so this is fully optional and backward
compatible. See the shipped `architecture-extraction` (a `relations` spine) and
`lit-review-matrix` (per-dimension `connect_to`) for worked examples.

## Deferred / not yet shipped

- The cross-source `linker` and the `synthesizer` (authoring the spine prose, see
  "The synthesis stage") are orchestrator/human steps, not shipped agents. A
  schema's `synthesis` block gives cross-source synthesis a materialized home (the
  per-dimension + apex nodes every source's claims converge on) and the
  `synthesis_status` field tracks `scaffold` -> `materialized`, but the apex/dimension
  *prose* is authored by hand, not auto-drafted.
- Schemas do not support inheritance/composition yet -- duplicate shared
  dimensions across related rubrics.
- Notes are not stamped with the schema version that produced them, so a schema
  change does not auto-trigger a backfill.
